{"/service/ndnp/curiv/batch_curiv_paperflower_ver01/data/sn92070146/0041418859A/1930121101/1082.xml":{"full_text":"6\nREQUESTS FOR\nGAME TICKETS\nPROVING HEAVY\nPASADENA, Dec. 11. (Special)\u2014\nTicket applications for the Alaba\nma-Washington State Rose Bowl\nfootball game have been remark\nably heavy during the first week,\nEarl V. Foster. general director, an\nnounced. Blanks were mailed to\n45 000 persons on the conference\nmailing lists while chambers of\ncommerce in 70 Southern Califor\nnia communities also distributed\nthe ticket forms.\nAll ticket applications should be\nreturned to the general headquar\nters, Pacific Southwest Building.\nPasadena, before December 15. Af\nter that day the tickets will be\nplaced on general sale and mail\napplications will be filled out ot\nthe remaining tickets.\nThe policy of \u201cfirst come first\nserved\" adopted by the game man\nagement in the sale of tickets has\nbrought immediate response from\nthose wishing choice scats. Because\nof the small following of alumni of\nthe respective rival teams, the\npublic is enjoying the privilege of\nbuying the best seats in the bowl.\nFor several years the center sec\ntions have been taken by the alum\nni groups of the participating\nschools.\nThe Palo Verde Valley has 240\nacres of pecans, some of them four\nyears old and bearing good crops for\nyoung trees.\nBERNARD LARRAN\u2019S\nClosing Out Sale\nOn the Newguier ranch, 1 mile south of Heber postoffice, 1 mile north\nof double main canal.\nSALE COMMENCES AT 11 O\u2019CLOCK SHARP\nTHURSDAY, DECEMBER 18TH\nFREE LUNCH AT NOON\n30 CHOICE DAIRY COWS 30\n20 HOLSTEIN'S. 4 JERSEYS, 5 GURNSEYS\nNOTE \u20148 fresh cows. 7 springers, balance milking good. Mostly all\nyoung cows. Look 'em over.\nThree Holstein heifers. 2'i years old: 4 Gurnsey heifers. 2 years old:\n4 heifers 18 months old; 5 heifers 8 months old: 3 heifers 3 months old.\nRegistered Guernsey bull. 4 years old.\nHORSES \u2014One span good horses. 40 chickens.\nImplements\nWagon and rack: McCormick mower, almost new: 2-horse alfalfa\nrenovator: No. 17 DeLatal separator: cans, buckets and strainer; bull\npanels: 10<> posts; 4 cement troughs; old lumber; some furniture.\nNOTE\u2014Owner going back to France on a visit. Everything must sell.\nUSUAL TERMS\nC. 11. H. Small, Clerk Bernard Larran, Owner\nSECURITY FIRST NATIONAL BANK. EL CENTRO\nD. L. ZINN and F. W. ZINN, Auctioneers\nOffice 510 Main Street, El Centro\u2014Phone 172\nREFERENCE\u2014ANY BANK IN IMPERIAL VALLEY\n(Buy Y our Potatoes T omorrow and Saturday I\nDemand Fat Boy Potatoes\nf You May Get a $l.OO Bill I\nB A $1 hill will be put in one sack of every 25 sacks of Fat Boy Potatoes for the Special Sale of this I\nI famous brand of potatoes that the merchants of Imperial Valley are having Friday and Saturday. I\nI Your Grocer has them on sale tomorrow and Saturday. Get yours at a Bargain Price and per- I\nI Buy now for future use\u2014they will keep indefinitely. Remember, they will be back at the regu-\nI Insist On Fat Boy Potatoes With Your Grocery Order I\nI \u201cThey Are the Best\u201d I\nI Packed by MAGGIO BROS. Exclusively\nAir Hero Breaks\nPledge\u2014and Jail\nMajor Ramon Franco, above.\nSpain's most famous flyer and one\ntime national idol, became a fugi\ntive from justice when, with an\nother aviator, he escaped from the\nold convent where he had been con\nfined for alleged seditious writings.\nFranco is understood to have given\nhis pledge that he would not at-\nI tempt escaoe. and it is said chat\nj his name had appeared on the list\nI of Christmas pardons.\nIMPERIAL VALLEY PRESS, EL CENTRO CALIFORNIA, THURSDAY, DECEMBER 11, 1980\nEXPERT REPORTS\nVALLEY BUSINESS\nCONDITIONS GOOD\nBusiness conditions in Imperia!\nValley have been tabulated for the\nLos Angeles Chamber of Commerce\nBulletin, published weekly, by Har\nold W. Wright, who recently made\na survey of business conditions in\nthis territory to compare with the\nbusiness outlook in other sections ot\nthe west. While in El Centro\nWright communicated with Frank\nGreene, manager of Bradstreet's and\nin charge of the nation's business\nmap on business conditions here,\nand sent in a very favorable report\nin favor of Imperial Valley remain\ning on the map as a white root.\nThe report in the Los Angeles\nChamber bulletin will give this sec\ntion of the state very favorable and\nwell merited publicity on the sound\nconditions existing here. Wright\nreports the agricultural condition as\nfair for November, with grapefruit\nand asparagus bringing a good price\nand the outlook for the lettuce crop\nindicating the largest acreage in\nthe history of the valley. Business\nconditions, he stated, are good, and\nmost merchants report a volume ot\nbusiness equal to last year, with El\nCentro and Brawley the best busi\nness cities, although credits are\nslowing up.\nThe fact that the cities of El\nCentro. Brawley and Calexico show\na volume of building permits sub\nstantially ahead of the same period\ntor 1929 is brought out in Wrights\nreport and the tourist travel is re\nported about the same as for 1929.\n\u201cA consistent effort is being made\nby the chamber of commerce to sec\nthat the various reports made on\nImperial Valley are correct and re\nflect true conditions.\" states R. B\nWhitelaw. president of the El Centro\nchamber. \"There is no question\nconcerning the soundness of busi\nness conditions here as compared\nwith other sections of the United\nStates, but persons coming here to\nmake a survey are very apt to get\none sided reports, and it is the\nintention of the chamber to avoid\nany chance of error by introducing\nthe visitors to local persons and\nfirms who will give them their per\nsonal opinions of existing condi\ntions in order that a number oi\nviewpoints may be considered and\na true general opinion formed. It\nis of the utmost importance to the\nvalley and its cities that only ac\ncurate surveys are made and that\nImperial County is represented as\nit should be with business sound\nand active.\"\nTruck Shipments\nRemain Heavy\nOutgoing shipments of farm pro\nducts from Imperial Valley checked\nat Trifoliuni by inspectors for the\nagricultural commissioner's office\nduring the week of November 30-\nJohn D. Saves a Nickel; He and Son Give Million for Jobless'\n\u201cMoney is scarce.\u2019\u2019 said John D. Rockefeller \u2014and in the picture at the top the 91-year-old magnate is shown\ngiving a bright new nickel instead of ills customary dime to the Rev. G. I). Owen, Ormond Leach. Fla., pas\ntor. But the next day Mr. Rockefeller and his son, John D. Rockefeller, Jr., contributed $1,000,000 lo a\ncampaign to provide employment for jobless heads of New York families. Below are two other remarkable\npictures of the aged multi-millionaire \u2014the first taken since his arrival at his winter home in Florida \u2014show-\ning him as he appeared on the golf course. Note the unusual cap designed to protect his head from undue\nexposure to the sun\u2019s rays.\nDecember 6 inclusive are given be\nlow:\nNinety-three tons cotton seed\nhulls. 122 bales cotton, 156 tons cot\nton seed meal, 1636 tons alfalfa\nhay, 3 tons barley, 134 tons milo\nmaize. 25 tons hides, 5\u2018- tons wool.\n402 tons manure. 222 head cattle.\n32 head hogs. 2 head horses, 142\ndozen turkeys, 137 dozen chickens.\n2599 crates peas. 156 crates squash,\n1451 crates cucumbers, 71 crates\nhoneydews, 7289 crates grapefruit.\n162 boxes tangerine. 112 boxes\noranges. 52 tons powdered milk.\nOutgoing shipments from the\nBoulder Park station consist of\n29\u2019i tons alfalfa hay. 5 tons milo\n'maize. 15 crates peas, 865 crates\ngrapefruit, 57 crates tangerines and\n18 trucks of miscellaneous products.\nCourt Severs\nMarital Bond\nLOS ANGELES. Dec. 11. (U.R)\nGraham C. Polk, Excelsior Springs.\nMo.. today was freed of the marital\nbonds which tied him to Lucille\nOrchard Polk, known on the stage\nas Lucille De Nevier. when an an\nnulment of the marriage was order\ned by Superior Judge Frank Collier.\nTestimony showed that the couple\nwere married at Seal Beach, Calif.,\non October 20. 1924, four days be\nfore Miss De Nevier's interlocutory\ndecree of divorce from Elta Or\nchard. oil promoter, became final.\nJudge Collier decided that the mar\ni iage license had been altered to\nmake it read October 29. 1921\ni Mrs. Polk has been married three\ni times. She was divorced in 1917\nfrom C. F. Durkis, former mayor of\nI Little Rock. Ark., and separated\nfrom Orchard, her second husband,\nin 1919. A reconciliation followed,\nhowever, which lasted until 1923\nwhen they were divorced.\nRobbers bound and gagged her\nin 1919. robbing her of $30,000 in\njewels, and it was while she was\nrecuperating from this shock at\nExcelsior Springs that she met\nPolk.\nThe Monterey Hotel, now ouilding\nat Blythe, Palo Verde Valley, will\ncost $175,000.\n1 J\nYaJKII a\nWNf* UM 1\nw X. QXATft\ny JlAm. 7*-^. LAAxr H\ncwCias tix JvSMF 4\nwTYh\nV QZdLJ J> if vtlK.\ny Jin//jflE\nv aIACt? XvtCw\nI s\nM aJct\nmStfhv\nr Ty o\ny __ A\ni C-HRJSTMAS\nI SMOKES j\nS\u2019 TAKE DAD. for instance. Supply him with his favorite\nj! brand of cigars, and you\u2019ve done more than wish him a\nMerry Christmas. You\u2019ve GIVEN him a Merry hristmas\nand a well-begun New Year, besides. The mans gift 4\nis\u2019 is smokes:\nWebster (Lords) 25\u2019s ,box $2.50\nf Chancellor (Liberty) 25 s, box $2.50 JL\nij Santa Fc (Biltmores) 10's, hox $1.2\u00bb\ny Santa Fe (Pttties) 25\u2019s, box $2.50 s\nSenta Fe (Invincibles) 25\u2019s, box $3.00\nCorina (Sunset) 25\u2019s, box $2.50 g\ny Corina (Queens) 25\u2019s, box M.OO g\ny Roi Tan (Perfectos) 25\u2019s, box $2.00 4\ny Roi Tan (Broadway) 25\u2019s, box $3.00\ng Rumidors, something new \u2014give genuine 2\nRum Flavor. $2.00 to $6.00 a\nXmas Packages Lucky Strikes, Old Golds, _ a\ng Chesterfields and Camels, carton $1.35 g\ny Xmas Ripes, Imported, new shapes, $1 to $5.00\nValley Drug Co. I\ny 505 M. .1. Horton Phone\nMain REX ALL S